name: Auth0
description: Auth0 is a cloud-based, extensible identity provider for various applications. The Sumo Logic App for Auth0 makes it easy to analyze and visualize your Auth0 logs, and provides insight into security and operational issues.

panels.name: Top 10 Clients
panels.queryString: $$logsrc | json "client_name" | where !isEmpty(client_name) | count client_name | top 10 client_name by _count

panels.name: Top 10 Recent Errors
panels.queryString: $$logsrc | json "type", "connection", "description", "client_name" | where type<>"slo" | count client_name, connection, description | top 10 client_name, connection, description by _count

panels.name: Logins by Client and Country
panels.queryString:
$$logsrc | json "client_name", "ip", "type"
| where type = "s"
| lookup country_name from geo://location on ip=ip
| count by client_name, country_name
| transpose row client_name column country_name

panels.name: Connection Types per Hour
panels.queryString: $$logsrc | json "connection" | where connection matches "*" | timeslice by 1h | count by _timeslice, connection | transpose row _timeslice column connection

panels.name: Logins by Client per Day
panels.queryString: $$logsrc | json "client_name", "type" | where client_name matches "*" and type = "s" | timeslice by 1d | count by _timeslice, client_name | transpose row _timeslice column client_name

panels.name: Client Version Usage
panels.queryString: $$logsrc | json "auth0_client.name", "auth0_client.version" | concat(%auth0_client.name, " ", %auth0_client.version) as auth0_client_version | timeslice 1h | count by _timeslice, auth0_client_version | transpose row _timeslice column auth0_client_version

panels.title: IPs with most anomaly detection events

queries.queryString:
$$logsrc
| json "data.type", "data.ip" as _type, ip
| where _type matches /^(limit_wc|limit_mu|pwd_leak)$/
| lookup country_name as Country, city as City from geo://location on ip
| ip as %"IP Address"
| count as Count by %"IP Address", City, Country
| sort by Count desc
| limit 5

$$logsrc
| json "data.type" as type | fields type | where type matches /^(fcoa|fu|f|fp)$/ 
| timeslice 1d 
| count by type, _timeslice
| transpose row _timeslice column type

// This is signups by day, by country 
// But having so many countries adds too much noise
_sourceCategory=engineering/log-stream-test
| json "data.type", "data.ip" as type, ip | fields type, ip 
| where type matches /^(ss)$/ 
| lookup country_name from geo://location on ip 
| timeslice 60 buckets
| count by _timeslice, country_name
| transpose row _timeslice column country_name

panels.text:
### Anomaly Detection Events
Events triggered by Auth0's Anomaly Detection features:
- `limit_wc`: Blocked IP address (single account fail)
- `limit_mu`: Blocked IP address (multiple account fail)
- `pwd_leak`: Breached password detected

queries.queryString:
$$logsrc
| json "data.type", "data.ip" as type, ip | fields type, ip | where type matches /^(fcoa|fu|f|fp)$/ | lookup country_name from geo://location on ip | count by country_name | top 10 country_name by _count

panels.title: IPs with the most login failures

queries.queryString:
$$logsrc
| json "data.type", "data.ip" as type, ip | fields type, ip | where type matches /^(fcoa|fu|f|fp|s|scoa|sens)$/ | lookup city as City, country_name as Country from geo://location on ip 
| ip as %"IP Address"
| count as Count by %"IP Address", Country, City 
| sort by Count 
| limit 10

panels.text:
### Login Failure Events
Events that signal a failed login:
- `f`: Failed login
- `fcoa`: Failed cross-origin authentication
- `fp`: Incorrect password
- `fu`: Incorrect username

A spike in failure events, particularly fu events, can be a sign of anomalous traffic on the login flow.

queries.queryString:
$$logsrc
| json "data.type" as type | fields type | where type matches /^(scoa|sens|s)$/ | timeslice 1d | count by type, _timeslice
| transpose row _timeslice column type

panels.text:
### Login Success Events
Events that signal a successful login:
- `s`: Successful Login
- `scoa`: Successful cross-origin authentication
- `sens`: Native social login

Successful logins follow predictable patterns on a timeframe basis.

queries.queryString:
$$logsrc
| json "data.type", "data.ip" as type, ip | fields type, ip | where type matches /^(scoa|sens|s)$/ 
| lookup latitude, longitude from geo://location on ip | count by latitude, longitude

$$logsrc
| json "data.type", "data.ip" as type, ip | fields type, ip | where type matches /^(fcoa|fu|f|fp)$/ 
| lookup latitude, longitude from geo://location on ip | count by latitude, longitude

panels.text:
### Number of unique IPs sending traffic
The number of IPs sending traffic should follow predictable traffic patterns by geolocation. Spikes could represent additional traffic due to a promotional campaign, but spikes could also be a sign of anomalous traffic.

### IPs with most login failures
A large number of failures from a single IP can signal anomalous traffic on the login flow.

### Account Creation Events in top countries
Account Creation events are organically predictable and can have surges after promotions or email campaigns. But very large spikes can signal an anomalous traffic on the creation flow.

### Account Creation Events by Platform
Surges in traffic from a particular platform (Windows, OSX, Android, iOS, etc) can help diagnose anomalous traffic.

### IPs with most Anomaly Detection Events
IP addresses triggering the most anomalous traffic. A surge of anomaly detection events from a limited number of IPs could signal an attack.

panels.title: Number of unique IPs sending traffic

queries.queryString:
$$logsrc
| json "data.type", "data.ip" as type, ip
| fields type, ip
| where type matches /^(fcoa|fu|f|fp|s|scoa|sens)$/
| timeslice 1d
| lookup country_name from geo://location on ip
| count_distinct(ip) group by country_name, _timeslice
| transpose row _timeslice column country_name

panels.text:
### Login failures by location
Login failures should follow predictable patterns for predictable geographies; spikes in traffic from unexpected locales are usually a sign of anomalous traffic.

queries.queryString:
_sourceCategory=engineering/log-stream-test
| json "data.description","log_id", "data.client_name", "data.type", "data.ip", "data.user_name" as %"Description", log_id, %"Client Name", %"Type", %"Client IP", %"Username"
| lookup country_name as Country from geo://location on ip=%"Client IP"
| formatDate(_messagetime, "yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss.SSS") as %"Date"
| count by log_id, _messagetime, %"Date", %"Client Name", Type, %"Client IP", Country, Username, Description
| sort by _messagetime
| fields - _count, log_id, _messagetime

panels.title: IPs with the most accounts created

queries.queryString:
_sourceCategory=engineering/log-stream-test

| json "data.type", "data.ip" as type, ip
| fields type, ip
| where type matches /^(ss)$/ 
| lookup city as City, country_name as Country from geo://location on ip 
| ip as %"IP Address"
| count as Count by %"IP Address", Country, City 
| sort by Count 
| limit 10

panels.text:
### IPs with most accounts created
Large number of accounts created from a single IP can signal an attack on the login flow.

panels.name: Top 10 Users by Successful Login
panels.queryString: $$logsrc | json "type", "user_name" | where type = "s" | where !isEmpty(user_name) | count user_name | top 10 user_name by _count

panels.name: Top 10 Users by Failed Login
panels.queryString: $$logsrc | json "type", "user_name" | where type in ("fp", "fu") | where !isEmpty(user_name) | count user_name | top 10 user_name by _count

panels.name: Top 10 Operating Systems
panels.queryString: $$logsrc | json "user_name", "user_agent", "client_name" | parse field=user_agent "/ * " as user_os | count_distinct(user_name) group by user_os | top 10 user_os by _count_distinct

panels.name: Login Event Geolocation
panels.queryString:
$$logsrc | json "ip", "type"
| where type = "s"
| lookup latitude, longitude, country_code, country_name, region, city from geo://location on ip = ip
| count by latitude, longitude, country_code, country_name, region, city
| sort _count

panels.name: Guardian MFA Activity
panels.queryString: $$logsrc | json "type" | where type matches("gd_*") | timeslice by 1h | count by _timeslice, type | transpose row _timeslice column type

panels.name: Top 10 User Agents
panels.queryString: $$logsrc | json "user_agent" | parse field=user_agent "* " as user_agent | count user_agent | top 10 user_agent by _count

panels.name: Top10 Source IPs by Failed Login
panels.queryString: $$logsrc | json "type", "ip" | where type in ("fp", "fu") | where !isEmpty(ip) | count ip | top 10 ip by _count

panels.name: Logins per Hour
panels.queryString:
$$logsrc | json "type" 
| if(type in ("fp", "fu"), "failure", if(type = "s", "success", "-")) as login_result
| where login_result != "-"
| timeslice 1h
| count by _timeslice, login_result
| transpose row _timeslice column login_result
